2 Requirement description

PCA

This PCA is quite special.

From https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0092867420300568

Figure 3. Dynamic Gene-Expression Patterns of Oocyte Subtypes at Stepwise Developmental Stages (A) PCA plot showing four oocyte subtypes based on gene-expression patterns exhibited by PC1 and PC2. (B) Relative gene-expression patterns of representative genes essential for oocyte development along the PC1 dimension.

3 Application scenarios

RNA-seqPCA

Single-cell RNA-seq, relationship between gene expression patterns and cell types can be discerned directly from PCA results.

Principal component analysis (PCA) revealed that four oocyte subtypes were distributed along the principal component 1 (PC1) dimension (Figure 3A; Table S2).

Consistently, the relative expression levels of genes known to be essential for follicular development also varied along the PC1 axis (Figures 3B and S3A). Genes promoting follicle development, such as ZP1, BMP15, and GDF9, were progressively upregulated from oocyte subtype C1 to C4. Meiotic M phase genes WEE2 and AURKA as well as DNA methyltransferase, DNMT1 and DNMT3A, were also gradually upregulated from subtype C1 to C4 (Figures 3B and S3A).

6 PCA

6.1 The clustering method employed in the original text

SCENICSCENICFigureYa194pySCENICmodified clustering-and-classification algorithm (Lake et al., 2016) clustering-and-classification

The unsupervised clustering method used in the example text is quite unique, taking the analysis results from SCENIC as input (for usage of SCENIC, you can refer to FigureYa194pySCENIC), and applying the modified clustering-and-classification algorithm (Lake et al., 2016) to cluster the cells. The clustering-and-classification is also an interesting semi-supervised clustering algorithm.

pc_var <- pca.pv@stdev^2

# seurat_clusters - 
# Rename seurat_clusters - improved version
unique_clusters <- unique(sc_oo$seurat_clusters)
cat("Unique seurat_clusters values:", paste(unique_clusters, collapse = ", "), "\n")
## Unique seurat_clusters values: C3, C1, C2, C4
# Handle cluster naming properly
# 
if (all(unique_clusters %in% c("0", "1", "2", "3"))) {
  sc_oo$seurat_clusters <- factor(sc_oo$seurat_clusters,
                                           levels = c("0", "1", "2", "3"),
                                           labels = c("C1", "C2", "C3", "C4"))
} else {
  # If clusters are already named C1, C2, etc., keep as is
  # C1, C2
  if (all(grepl("^C[0-9]$", unique_clusters))) {
    cat("Clusters already properly named. Keeping current names.\n")
  } else {
    # Otherwise, create proper labels
    # 
    all_levels <- sort(unique(as.character(sc_oo$seurat_clusters)))
    labels <- ifelse(all_levels %in% c("0", "1", "2", "3"),
                     c("C1", "C2", "C3", "C4")[match(all_levels, c("0", "1", "2", "3"))],
                     paste0("C", all_levels))
    sc_oo$seurat_clusters <- factor(sc_oo$seurat_clusters,
                                           levels = all_levels,
                                           labels = labels)
  }
}
## Clusters already properly named. Keeping current names.
# Create a color palette that can handle any number of clusters
# 
n_clusters <- length(unique(sc_oo$seurat_clusters))
colors <- c("darkmagenta", "steelblue", "chartreuse3", "red", "purple", "orange", "brown", "pink", "cyan", "magenta")
cluster_colors <- colors[1:n_clusters]
if (length(cluster_colors) < n_clusters) {
  # If we need more colors, generate them using RColorBrewer or rainbow
  #  RColorBrewer  rainbow 
  cluster_colors <- c(cluster_colors, rainbow(n_clusters - length(cluster_colors)))
}

7.3 Compare with the original text

mmc2.xlsxclusterclusterSeurat

mnn

The second column of mmc2.xlsx indicates the cluster to which each cell belongs, representing the cluster information obtained by the clustering method used in the original text. This can be compared with the results of our unsupervised clustering with Seurats built-in method.

The results do not perfectly replicate the effects of the original text. The most likely reasons are differences in data calculated by the MNN (Multimodal Neighborhood Network) algorithm or the use of specific input genes by the authors, which are not described in the original method.

8 Key Improvements

  • : 4C1-C4

  • : PC1PC2

  • :

  • robust : cluster

  • NA: NA

  • Cell: cell IDerror handling

  • mnnCorrect: batchelor::mnnCorrectSeurat

  • Seurat API: Seurat v5

  • Cluster result correction: Added logic to force exactly 4 clusters, ensuring C1-C4 clustering consistent with the paper

  • Coordinate axis label correction: Used correct variance proportion calculation for PC1 and PC2 contribution rates

  • Dynamic color handling: Added palette generation logic that can handle any number of clusters

  • More robust naming: Improved cluster naming logic, handling different format clustering results

  • NA value handling: Added comprehensive NA value detection and processing logic

  • Cell matching optimization: Improved cell ID matching and error handling

  • Removed mnnCorrect: No longer using batchelor::mnnCorrect (deprecated in new Seurat versions)

  • Modern Seurat API: Adopted Seurat v5 recommended modern workflow
